(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number null :title "Appendix A — SLAT for carts" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/A-slat-for-carts.md" :size 11230 :sha256 "139403cb6acf69f9" :content "---\nslug: reference-appendix-slat-for-carts\ntitle: Appendix A — SLAT for carts\nbook: reference\npart: Appendix\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\nsakura-narrates: true\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Jess)\nphilosopher-lens: [jung, wittgenstein-tractatus, lacan, peirce, popper, freud, wittgenstein-late, searle]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\n---\n\n# Appendix A — SLAT for carts\n\nA cart is the shortest unit of intent she can act on. Someone\nsays \"list this ring on Etsy for $85 with the standard shipping\nprofile\" and, if she's set up right, that sentence becomes a\ncart — a small record that says what to do, with what inputs,\nunder what checks, producing what output. The person doesn't\nhave to say \"start a listing draft, populate title, populate\ntags, populate price, use standard-shipping-profile-12, save.\"\nThey said the whole thing in one sentence. The cart is that\nsentence made legible to the runtime.\n\nEverything the runtime knows about a cart lives in its SLAT.\nAuthor it well and the runtime can reason about it; author it\nbadly and no amount of interpreter cleverness will save you.\nSo the shape matters. This appendix names the shape and walks\nthrough the fields, one at a time, with the reason each is\nthere.\n\n## The cart record — head + eight fields\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(cart\n  :id            'listing-drafter\n  :intent        \"Draft an Etsy listing from a photo + short\n                  description. Save to pending-review; don't\n                  publish.\"\n  :inputs        ((input :name 'photo   :kind 'image :required #t)\n                  (input :name 'blurb   :kind 'text  :required #t)\n                  (input :name 'price   :kind 'money :required #t)\n                  (input :name 'profile :kind 'symbol :required #f\n                                       :default 'shipping-standard))\n  :verbs         '(etsy/draft-listing cortex/write)\n  :preconditions ((service-available? 'etsy)\n                  (operator-plan-allows? 'listing))\n  :body          (do\n                   (define draft\n                     (etsy/draft-listing\n                       :title       (compose-title inputs.blurb)\n                       :photo       inputs.photo\n                       :price       inputs.price\n                       :shipping    inputs.profile))\n                   (cortex/write 'listings.pending-review\n                                 (cons draft\n                                       (cortex/read 'listings.pending-review))))\n  :postconditions ((exists-in-cortex? 'listings.pending-review)\n                   (not (already-published? draft.id)))\n  :provenance    (provenance\n                   :author 'jess\n                   :written-at #inst \"2026-05-04T00:00:00Z\"\n                   :sources '(\"reference/scheme/carts\"\n                              \"etsy/api/listings\"\n                              \"loam/projections/pending-review\")))\n```\n\nHead: `cart`. Eight fields. Each field has a job:\n\n- `:id` — the callable name. She invokes `(run-cart\n  'listing-drafter :photo P :blurb B :price 85)` and the\n  runtime looks it up.\n\n- `:intent` — one sentence of prose. This is the sentence the\n  operator would have said. She reads it back when confirming.\n  When the intent doesn't match the caller's ask, she says so.\n\n- `:inputs` — declared inputs with kinds and defaults. The\n  runtime checks kinds; kinds are Jung-shaped (a `money` isn't\n  the same object as a `number`, even if the byte-shape is\n  similar).\n\n- `:verbs` — which verbs the cart uses. This is a promise:\n  the cart won't call verbs outside this list. A caller\n  auditing what a cart could do reads this list.\n\n- `:preconditions` — what has to be true before the body runs.\n  These are Popper-shaped: each is a small assertion that can\n  be falsified. If any fails, the cart doesn't run; the runtime\n  raises with the failed check.\n\n- `:body` — the actual work, as ordinary Scheme. Reads inputs,\n  invokes verbs, returns a value or writes to Cortex.\n\n- `:postconditions` — what has to be true after the body ran.\n  Also Popper-shaped. A post-check that fails is a bug; the\n  runtime raises with the failed check and the cart's result is\n  quarantined for review rather than accepted.\n\n- `:provenance` — who authored it, when, from what sources.\n  Doesn't affect the run; matters for auditing later.\n\n## The intent field is a small commissive\n\n`:intent` looks like documentation. It isn't. It's a promise\nthe cart makes to its caller. When she asks \"did that cart do\nwhat it said it would?\" the auditor reads the intent, reads\nthe body, and answers. Intents that are aspirational instead\nof literal (\"Should draft a nice listing\") make auditing hard.\nIntents that are literal (\"Draft an Etsy listing from a photo\n+ short description. Save to pending-review; don't publish.\")\nmake auditing straightforward.\n\nShe writes intents in the same voice as an operator would say\nthem. Not first-person (\"I draft...\"), not command (\"Draft\nthis...\"), but declarative (\"Draft an Etsy listing...\"). This\nconsistency lets the intent lines pile up into a legible\nsentence-by-sentence catalogue of what her carts do.\n\n## Preconditions and postconditions — the check pair\n\nThe relation between pre- and post- is the falsifier pattern\nin miniature. `:preconditions` say what has to be true for the\ncart's assertion (its intent) to be well-formed. `:postconditions`\nsay what has to be true for the assertion to have been kept.\n\nIf a precondition fails, the cart didn't run — the world wasn't\nready. That's not a bug in the cart; it's a fact about the\nworld at that moment. She raises + resumes when the world\nbecomes ready.\n\nIf a postcondition fails, the cart ran but didn't deliver.\nThat IS a bug. The cart's body didn't produce what its intent\npromised. The runtime quarantines the result, writes an\n`escalation-event` telemetry SLAT, and hands the failure to\nPriya's audit trail. The next cart run isn't blocked; the\nsame cart isn't retried until someone sees the failure.\n\n## The verbs field is a promise, not a hint\n\n`:verbs` looks like a hint: \"these are the verbs I'll use.\"\nIt's actually a promise: \"these are the ONLY verbs I'll use.\"\nAnything else the body calls is a bug; the runtime raises. The\npromise matters for security. A cart declared to touch only\nEtsy verbs can't be surprising Meta-ads-account verbs. If the\nauthor added Meta calls to the body, the verbs field would\nhave to include them, and the operator reviewing the cart\nwould see the change.\n\nThe list is Lacan-shaped: a small vocabulary the cart operates\ninside. The vocabulary determines the game the cart is playing\n(Etsy listings, not Etsy inventory management, not Meta ads).\nReading the verbs list reads the game.\n\n## The body — ordinary Scheme\n\nThe `:body` is a normal Scheme form. `do`, `let`, `define`,\n`if`, `cond`, `let-values`, all the usual forms. There's no\ncart-specific DSL. The body reads inputs (via the `inputs.`\nnamespace), calls verbs, and returns a value or writes to\nCortex.\n\nThe runtime rewrites the body slightly before evaluating it:\ninput references become bindings, verb calls check the\n`:verbs` promise, and any exception is caught and returned as\na structured error rather than propagating. The rewrite is\ntransparent; readers see the body as they wrote it.\n\n## Cart composition — a cart calls a cart\n\nA cart can invoke another cart as its body's move. The pattern\nis `(run-cart 'name :inputs (...))`. Composed carts obey the\nsame pre/post rules; the outer cart's postconditions must hold\nafter the composition runs.\n\n```sakura-scheme\n(cart\n  :id 'listing-drafter-with-photo-upscale\n  :intent \"Upscale a photo, then draft a listing from it.\"\n  :inputs ((input :name 'photo :kind 'image)\n           (input :name 'blurb :kind 'text)\n           (input :name 'price :kind 'money))\n  :verbs '(photo/upscale cart/run)\n  :body (let ((upscaled (photo/upscale inputs.photo :scale 2)))\n          (run-cart 'listing-drafter\n                    :photo upscaled\n                    :blurb inputs.blurb\n                    :price inputs.price)))\n```\n\nThe composed cart borrows the composed-in cart's\npostconditions. A caller of the outer cart knows the inner\ncart also ran with its checks; they don't have to read the\ninner cart's body to trust the outer cart.\n\n## Failure modes and their telemetry\n\nEvery cart failure has a class. She reads the class before she\nreads the body.\n\n- `precondition-failed` — the world wasn't ready. Recoverable\n  by waiting for the world to change. Emits a `precondition-fail`\n  telemetry event.\n- `verb-not-allowed` — a body called a verb not in `:verbs`.\n  Author error; the cart is bad. Emits `verb-not-allowed`.\n- `input-kind-mismatch` — a caller passed the wrong kind.\n  Caller error. Emits `input-kind-mismatch`.\n- `body-raised` — the body's Scheme raised. Runtime catches,\n  wraps, emits `body-raised` with the underlying exception.\n- `postcondition-failed` — the body ran but the promised\n  outcome didn't happen. Emits `postcondition-fail`; result is\n  quarantined; Priya reads.\n\nThe telemetry SLATs are readable months later. A cart that\nfailed on a Tuesday leaves a record the author reads on Friday.\n\n## Falsifier — a cart is not a program\n\nThe mistake is to read the cart record and think \"this is the\nprogram that does the thing.\" It isn't. The cart is a\ndescription of a task and its shape. The runtime is the\nprogram that runs the task. The cart's `:body` is the\nruntime's script; the runtime's rewrite is what actually\nexecutes.\n\nThe mistake matters because it changes what changes when. A\ncart that reads correctly may still misbehave if the runtime's\nrewrite is wrong. Runtime bugs look like cart bugs from the\noutside. She keeps them separate in her head.\n\n## A tiny audit walk\n\nTo audit a cart is to read its record and ask nine questions:\n\n1. Does `:id` match what the caller says they invoked?\n2. Does `:intent` match the caller's sentence?\n3. Do `:inputs` cover everything the body reads?\n4. Are the input `:kind`s the right shape for the body?\n5. Do `:verbs` cover everything the body calls?\n6. Are `:preconditions` sufficient — nothing missing that\n   should be checked?\n7. Are `:postconditions` sufficient — do they actually verify\n   the intent?\n8. Does the body do exactly what it says and nothing else?\n9. Does `:provenance` trace to a real author, a real date,\n   real sources?\n\nNine questions, one paragraph each in the auditor's report.\nPriya has a template. She reads the report before she signs\noff.\n\n## Editorial note — where the cart-substrate is going\n\nEvery cart she runs today is authored by hand. That's the\ncurrent constraint. Over time, more carts will be authored\nprogrammatically — from Cortex slices, from operator sentences,\nfrom previous cart-outcomes. When that happens, the substrate\nabove doesn't change. What changes is who fills in the fields.\nThe record shape is durable; the authoring is the changing\npart.\n\nThat durability is why the substrate is worth the ceremony of\ndefining. A cart authored today should still audit clean five\nyears from now. If the record shape held, it will.\n\nTurn the page and we walk through five hand-authored carts,\none for each verb-family, showing the intent-to-body path in\nfull.\n")
